Etymology 1[edit]

From re- (“again”) +‎ legō (“choose, gather”).

Pronunciation[edit]

  • (Classical) IPA(key): /ˈre.le.ɡoː/, [ˈrɛ.lɛ.ɡoː]
  • (Ecclesiastical) IPA(key): /ˈre.le.ɡo/, [ˈrɛː.lɛ.ɡɔ]

Verb[edit]

relegō (present infinitive relegere, perfect active relēgī, supine relēctum); third conjugation

  1. I gather, collect again, recover.
  2. I travel, traverse or sail over or through again.
  3. I go over or go through again in reading, speech, thought, read, relate or recite again, revise, recount.

Etymology 2[edit]

From re- (“back, again”) +‎ lēgō (“send, dispatch”).

Pronunciation[edit]

  • (Classical) IPA(key): /reˈleː.ɡoː/, [rɛˈleː.ɡoː]
  • (Ecclesiastical) IPA(key): /reˈle.ɡo/, [rɛˈlɛː.ɡɔ]

Verb[edit]

relēgō (present infinitive relēgāre, perfect active relēgāvī, supine relēgātum); first conjugation

  1. I despatch, send away.
  2. I banish, remove to a distance.
  3. (figuratively) I put aside, reject, remove; shift.
  4. (figuratively) I refer (to a book or author), attribute, ascribe.
  5. I bequeath.
